docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:12:| A-008 | `GET /api/v1/auth/me/` uses session-bound access validation: the access token must verify by signature/expiry/type and its `session_id` must reference an active `UserSession` whose user can still authenticate. `auth_service.validate_access_token` remains the low-level stateless decode helper for callers that only need JWT validation. | `auth-permissions.md` says access tokens include `session_id`, session tracking is required, inactive users must be blocked, and the slice requires revoked sessions to be rejected for current-user data. | `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §5.2-5.3, §7.1-7.3, §8.2; `docs/source/technical-architecture.md` §10.1-10.3 | 002D-current-user-api-with-permissions-and-teams | Medium | No | 2026-07-03 | Resolved by 002D on 2026-07-03: `auth_service.validate_access_session()` and `current_user_payload_for_access_token()` enforce active session + active user for `/auth/me/`; tests cover logout-revoked sessions and suspended users. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:13:| A-009 | The safe development default for `SFPCL_ALLOWED_HOSTS` is `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, and Django's `testserver`. | Slice 002D2 says the default should be localhost; adding loopback IP and test client host is the standard Django local/test default and avoids `ALLOWED_HOSTS` failures without using `"*"`. | `docs/slices/002D2-backend-dev-infrastructure.md`, `docs/working/DECISION_POLICY.md` §3 | 002D2-backend-dev-infrastructure | Low | No | 2026-07-03 | Production/staging can override with comma-separated `SFPCL_ALLOWED_HOSTS`; no business rule affected. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:15:| A-011 | The tracer-only canonical permission is `tracer.lifecycle.run`; it is intentionally not part of the source RBAC catalogue and is granted only in tests/dev smoke setup for the early end-to-end proof. The guarded demo seed isolates this grant on the local/dev-only `local_demo_tracer_user` role so shared source-catalogue roles such as `sales_team_user` stay permission-neutral. | 002EX needs one explicit route/action permission without inventing broad member/finance grants or changing source RBAC rules before real modules arrive. 002K2 corrected the demo seed so the smoke permission does not become a source role grant. | `docs/slices/002EX-early-end-to-end-tracer-bullet.md`, `docs/slices/002K2-demo-tracer-permission-isolation.md`, `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §3, `docs/working/DECISION_POLICY.md` §1.3 | 002EX-early-end-to-end-tracer-bullet, 002EY-e2e-and-visual-regression-harness, 002K2-demo-tracer-permission-isolation | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-04 | Later production slices must replace this tracer-only permission with real module permissions and remove or isolate the dev tracer route before production hardening. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:17:| A-013 | The Playwright suite and its committed screenshot baselines are AUTHORED in the AFK run but must be RUN and generated on a networked machine with browsers. This sandbox binds localhost (002EX EPERM resolved) but has no network, so `@playwright/test` + Chromium cannot install and the suite cannot execute here. | Run rules: pin the dependency, write code/tests, note the missing module, finish; the orchestrator/operator installs and runs before the visual-evidence loop is closed. Hard gates never run Playwright (`e2e_tests: optional`; no e2e gate in ralph-validate.sh). | `docs/slices/002EY-e2e-and-visual-regression-harness.md` (reqs 3,4,10,12,13,15), `sfpcl-lms/e2e/README.md`, `.ralph/config.yaml` | 002EY-e2e-and-visual-regression-harness | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-04 | Operator: `cd sfpcl-lms && npm install && npx playwright install chromium && E2E_DJANGO_PYTHON=../.ralph/venv/bin/python npm run e2e -- --update-snapshots`, commit `e2e/*-snapshots/`, then the owner may flip `quality_gates.e2e_tests` from `optional` (protected config) once the suite is stable. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:18:| A-014 | Admin user-management must block any role or status change that would leave zero active users whose primary role is `system_admin`. The guard applies when changing a user's primary role away from `system_admin` or setting a `system_admin` user's status to anything other than `active`. | Source docs require System Administrator user/role administration and suspended users being denied access, but do not state the exact lock-out rule. Slice 002G requires the default guard to prevent removing or suspending the last active `system_admin`. | `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §12.1, §15.12; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §12; `docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md` | 002G-admin-user-and-role-management-shell | Medium | No | 2026-07-04 | Implemented as an API validation rule returning `400 VALIDATION_ERROR` with `field_errors.status` or `field_errors.role_code`; future account lifecycle slices may refine this if source docs add a more specific break-glass process. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:19:| A-015 | Admin user list/detail read is gated by `users.user.read` OR any write user-admin permission (`users.user.create`/`update`/`disable`). §19 maps `/settings/users` to `users.user.read`, but the seeded `system_admin` role (`catalogue.py`) holds create/update/disable and NOT `users.user.read`, so a read-only gate would lock the platform's only seeded user-admin out of the screens it must operate. | Preserve current `system_admin` read access (slice 002G2 req 2/5) without inventing a new `users.user.read` seed grant for `system_admin` — that would be a source-doc change (§15.12 lists System Administrator key permissions without `users.user.read`). Write actions stay gated by their specific §12.1 permission. | `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §12.1, §15.12, §19; `sfpcl_credit/identity/catalogue.py`; `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/admin_users.py` | 002G2-admin-user-action-permission-granularity | Medium | No | 2026-07-04 | If source docs later add `users.user.read` to the System Administrator grant (or a dedicated read-only user-admin role), tighten `READ_USERS_PERMISSION_CODES` to `{users.user.read}` and update the seed + tests. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:21:| A-017 | The `GET /api/v1/audit-logs/` list orders newest-first by `created_at` with `audit_log_id` as a deterministic secondary tiebreak, uses `page_size` default 20 / max 100 (mirroring the 002G admin-user list), and rejects any query parameter outside `{entity_type, entity_id, actor_user_id, page, page_size}` with `400 VALIDATION_ERROR`. `user_agent` is stored on `AuditLog` but not exposed, matching the §42.1 item shape. | `api-contracts.md` §42.1 fixes the item fields and newest-first intent but is silent on tiebreak, page-size bounds, and unknown-parameter strictness; these are boring industry-standard defaults consistent with the existing admin list and the slice's "unknown filters return 400" rule. | `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §42.1; `docs/slices/003A-audit-log-foundation.md`; `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/admin_users.py` | 003A-audit-log-foundation | Low | No | 2026-07-04 | If source docs later specify a different audit ordering, page-size ceiling, or additional filters, extend `identity/modules/audit_log.py` and its tests accordingly. |
