docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:19:- Auth behavior moved behind explicit module functions in `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/`: `tokens.py` (encode/decode/hash/claims + `TokenError`) and `auth_service.py` (`authenticate_user`/`CredentialError`, `issue_login_tokens_and_session`, `validate_refresh_session`, `rotate_refresh_token`, `revoke_session_for_logout`, `validate_access_token`, `record_auth_event`, `auth_payload`). Views are now thin (parse → call module → translate errors). `views.py` re-exports `TokenError` and `decode_token` for backward-compatible imports.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:20:- All 002B/002B2 behavior preserved (verified by unchanged `test_auth_api.py` + new `test_auth_module.py`): PyJWT HS256, lifetimes, claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, audit events.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:24:- Current-user reads use `auth_service.current_user_payload_for_access_token()`, which calls the new session-bound `validate_access_session()`: access token must be signed, unexpired, type `access`, bound to an active `UserSession`, and owned by a user whose status can authenticate.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:29:- Tests added in `test_auth_api.py` and `test_auth_module.py`: success envelope/meta, missing token, expired token, refresh misuse, inactive user, revoked session, permission sorting/empty cases, available actions, and thin-view service-boundary guardrail.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:47:  - 002D2 should remove duplicated backend test schema setup. Current tests repeat `django.setup()` + `schema_editor.create_model()` helpers in `test_auth_api.py`, `test_auth_module.py`, `test_api_envelope.py`, and `test_catalogue_seed.py`; after 002D2 they should rely on Django's migrated test database/shared test base.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:51:- 002EX now explicitly depends on 002E and 002D2: its tracer screen must run through authenticated staff session state, use real APIs and persistent dev SQLite for manual smoke evidence, keep automated tests on the migrated Django test database, and include an unauthenticated `401` envelope regression for at least one tracer endpoint.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:56:- Source extracts for the 2026-07-03_224536 review: `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §11.4 defines `/auth/me/` profile + roles + teams + permissions; its closing implementation rule says React uses `available_actions` for UX while Django remains authoritative. `docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md` §10.6 says UI navigation must be role-aware and backend rejects unauthorized API calls. `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §13.1 includes role codes `it_head`, `internal_auditor`, `management_viewer`, and others that the frontend bridge must handle explicitly or neutrally.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:58:- 002EY should make Playwright prove the same production/default auth path. Its login flow must hit the dev Django server and should include negative browser checks that missing/revoked sessions land on staff login and zero-permission/unmapped backend roles cannot expose tracer routes/actions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:60:- 002EX completed the first real integration proof: minimal `tracer` Django app, one migration, session-bound `/api/v1/tracer/...` endpoints, service-layer transition guards, one audit log and one workflow event per transition, a staff-shell Tracer screen, and a narrow `tracer.lifecycle.run` permission bridge. Source extracts used: `api-contracts.md` §3 requires backend-enforced workflow, explicit action endpoints, auditability, versioned `/api/v1/`, and standard envelopes; `data-model.md` §26.1-26.2 defines append-only audit logs and workflow events. Browser screenshots remain deferred to 002EY because this sandbox blocked localhost binding with `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:61:- 002F completed the role-aware shell hardening: `PAGE_PERMISSIONS` and `resolveNavigationAttempt()` now live in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar.tsx` exports the canonical staff nav table for parity tests, and `App.tsx` uses the shared guard helper. Frontend tests assert every non-dashboard staff nav item is gated by the same prototype permission as its page, blocked navigation returns to Dashboard with `blockedPage`, `tracer.lifecycle.run` maps only to `run_tracer`, and unknown/empty-role current-user responses stay neutral. The 002EY `auth-negative` Playwright spec was extended for zero-permission, tracer-only, and invalid stored-session restore checks; local browser execution remained blocked by sandbox localhost `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:69:- 002F2 completed the shallow Sidebar visibility corrective slice: `visibleStaffNavItems()` now lives in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar` consumes it with `allNavItems`, and vitest covers the actual visibility path plus direct route guard behavior for every protected item, zero-permission backend sessions, unknown/empty-role backend sessions, and tracer-only sessions. `tracer.lifecycle.run` still maps only to `run_tracer` and unlocks only Dashboard + Tracer.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:73:- For 002I: build only a domain-neutral object-level permission helper/test harness. It should accept explicit actor permissions/team codes plus object owner/team facts, allow owner or matching team access, deny missing module permission as `PERMISSION_DENIED`, deny mismatched or unknown object scope as object access denied, and avoid adding public endpoints or querying future loan/member/application tables.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:74:- 002H completed the shared workflow guard foundation. `sfpcl_credit/workflows/guard.py` defines domain-neutral transition definitions/results plus typed errors for unknown action, missing permission, and invalid state. Tracer services now pass explicit actor permission codes into the shared guard for lifecycle actions while preserving existing tracer URLs, success payloads, `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`, audit logs, and workflow events. No schema change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:77:- 002I completed the object-level permission test harness. `sfpcl_credit.identity.modules.object_permissions.evaluate_object_access(...)` is a pure domain-neutral helper that accepts only explicit actor facts (`actor_user_id`, `actor_team_codes`, `actor_permission_codes`) and object facts (`required_permission`, `object_owner_user_id`, `object_team_code`, optional `allow_global`). It returns `ObjectAccessResult(allowed, reason, error_code, required_permission, approval_required)`; missing module permission returns `missing_permission` / `PERMISSION_DENIED`; owner and team matches allow; mismatched or unknown scope returns `owner_mismatch`, `team_mismatch`, or `scope_unknown` with `OBJECT_ACCESS_DENIED`; `scope_unknown` sets `approval_required=True`; explicit `allow_global=True` permits unknown scope only after the required canonical permission is present. Tests verify use with `auth_service.effective_permission_codes(user)`, `User.team_codes()`, and `auth_service.team_payload(user)`. No endpoint, schema change, domain model query, audit row, or frontend change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:83:- 002K2 corrected the guarded demo tracer grant after architecture review: `demo.tracer@sfpcl.example` now uses local/dev-only role `local_demo_tracer_user` with exactly A-011 `tracer.lifecycle.run`, while the shared source-catalogue `sales_team_user` role remains permission-neutral. Regression coverage creates a non-demo `sales_team_user`, reruns the guarded seed, logs in through `/auth/login/`, and verifies `/auth/me/` returns `permissions: []` and `available_actions: []`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:84:- Architecture review is due after 002K by cadence (`slices_completed_since_architecture_review` reaches 4). 003A has already been sharpened to add only a protected paginated `GET /api/v1/audit-logs/` over the existing `identity.AuditLog` model, using `audit.audit_log.read` as the narrowest existing audit-read permission. 003B has been sharpened to reconcile the pre-existing tracer-owned `workflow_events` table before creating/owning any canonical workflow-event foundation.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:93:- Permission naming convention: §11 (verbs in §11.1); full permission catalogue by module: §12.1–12.13 (auth/user-admin, members, KYC, applications, credit assessment, approvals, documentation, security, SAP/finance, monitoring/default, closure, compliance, reports/audit/config).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:110:- `docs/source/technical-architecture.md` §13.1 says Django views should not contain complex workflow orchestration; multi-entity operations, permissions, calculations, and audit logs belong in explicit service classes/functions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:111:- `docs/source/codebase-design.md` §6-7 says workflow/business logic should live behind explicit module interfaces and tests should exercise those interfaces, not scattered helpers.

